# OPERATIONAL DIRECTIVES

ALWAYS use PAG keywords in uppercase
ALWAYS define $ARGUMENTS or positional parameters explicitly
ALWAYS document what each argument does
ALWAYS test command before deploying
ALWAYS specify allowed-tools if restricting access
ALWAYS include usage examples

NEVER use both $ARGUMENTS and $1/$2/$3 ambiguously
NEVER skip frontmatter validation
NEVER create commands without description
NEVER reference undefined arguments
NEVER use tools not listed in allowed-tools
NEVER leave commands.template in commands folder after creation

## Template Removal

WHEN command_creation_complete:
IF ".claude/commands/commands.template" EXISTS:
DELETE ".claude/commands/commands.template"
REPORT "Template cleanup complete"

# NEW FEATURES (v2.1.0+)

## Context Forking for Commands

SET context = "fork" TO run command in isolated sub-agent:
- Separate conversation history
- No main conversation pollution
- Useful for research/analysis commands
- Parallel execution support

## Agent Specification

SET agent = "agent-type" TO use specific agent for command:
- "general-purpose" - Default all-purpose agent
- "Explore" - Fast codebase exploration
- "Plan" - Planning and architecture
- Custom agents from .claude/agents/

## Command-Scoped Hooks

DEFINE hooks = [
{
"type": "PreToolUse",
"command": "echo 'Command starting'",
"once": false
},
{
"type": "PostToolUse",
"command": "validation command"
},
{
"type": "Stop",
"command": "cleanup command"
}
]

# NOTES

- Filename (without .md) becomes the command name
- Commands are slash-invoked by users: `/command-name args`
- Dynamic placeholders are replaced at runtime
- File references (@file) inject content directly
- Bash commands (!) execute during command processing
- Project commands override user commands with same name
- Use `context: fork` for isolation from main conversation
- Use `hooks:` for lifecycle control (v2.1.0+)
